      "question": "The graph of a polynomial $p(x)$ is given in the figure below. Based on the geometrical representation, determine the number of zeros of the polynomial $p(x)$ and justify your answer by describing how the graph relates to the zeros of the polynomial.",
      "answer": "The polynomial $p(x)$ has $3$ zeros. The zeros are the $x$-coordinates of the points where the graph intersects the $x$-axis.",
      "solution": {
        "steps": [
          "Observe the number of intersection points between the curve of the polynomial $y = p(x)$ and the $x$-axis.",
          "The graph intersects the $x$-axis at three distinct points: $x = -2$, $x = 1$, and $x = 3$.",
          "By the geometrical meaning of zeros, the $x$-coordinates of the points where the graph of $y = p(x)$ intersects the $x$-axis are the zeros of the polynomial $p(x)$.",
          "Since there are three such intersection points, the polynomial has exactly $3$ zeros."
        ],
        "derivation": "p(x) \\text{ intersects the } x\\text{-axis at } (-2, 0), (1, 0), \\text{ and } (3, 0) \\\\ \\text{Number of intersection points} = 3 \\\\ \\text{Therefore, the number of zeros of } p(x) = 3"
      },
